T1  - Market evidence on the opaqueness of banking firms’ assets
AU  - Flannery, Mark J.
AU  - Kwan, Simon H.
AU  - Nimalendran, M.
JO  - Journal of Financial Economics
VL  - 71
IS  - 3
SP  - 419
EP  - 460
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/03/01/
SN  - 0304-405X
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0304-405X(03)00185-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0304405X03001855
KW  - Banks
KW  - Microstructure
KW  - Opacity
AB  - We assess the market microstructure properties of U.S. banking firms’ equity, to determine whether they exhibit more or less evidence of asset opaqueness than similar-sized nonbanking firms. The evidence indicates that large bank holding companies (BHC), traded on the NYSE, have very similar trading properties to their matched nonfinancial firms. In contrast, smaller BHCs, traded on NASDAQ, trade much less frequently despite having very similar spreads. Analysis of IBES earnings forecasts indicates that banking assets are not unusually opaque; they are simply boring. The implications for regulatory policy and future market microstructure research are discussed.
ER  - 

